<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n17024e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n17" href="#n17024e">N17 (VI.B.9)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n17all.htm#n17024e"> 24(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> G cannot under-/stand living / men only / the dead</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&hellip; the nerves of <i>living</i> men, especially when in a condition of <i>intense excitement</i>, may exercise such a powerful attraction upon the nerves of God that he cannot get free from them again, and thus his own existence may be threatened. This exceedingly rare occurrence took place in Schreber&apos;s case and involved him in the greatest sufferings. The instinct of self-preservation was aroused in God, and then it became evident that God was far removed from the perfection ascribed to him by religions. Through the whole of Schreber&apos;s book there runs the bitter complaint that <mark>God, being only accustomed to communication with the dead, <i>does not understand living men</i></mark>. <small> Sigmund Freud, <a name="SFPS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SFPS"><cite title="source">&ldquo;Psychoanalytical Notes on an Autobiographic Account of a Case of Paranoia (Dementia Paranoides)&rdquo;</cite></a> (1925) 405</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
